<paragraph blockId="17.[191,1440,1763,1927]" lastBlockId="18.[191,1442,1249,1746]" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="17" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,321,1763,1789]" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">Definition.</emphasis>
Sequencing of the 
<taxonomicName authority="Mabille and Boullet, 1912" authorityName="Mabille and Boullet" authorityYear="1912" box="[545,1047,1763,1789]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Nascus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diaphorus">
<emphasis box="[545,742,1763,1789]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">Nascus diaphorus</emphasis>
Mabille and Boullet, 1912
</taxonomicName>
(type locality 
<collectingCountry box="[1215,1325,1763,1790]" name="Suriname" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">Suriname</collectingCountry>
) 
<typeStatus box="[1342,1440,1763,1789]" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">holotype</typeStatus>
(NVG-18086A07, EL63162) in MNHP reveals that it is a taxon closely related to 
<taxonomicName authority="Evans, 1952" authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1952" box="[1082,1440,1797,1824]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Dyscophellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ramon">
<emphasis box="[1082,1302,1797,1823]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">Dyscophellus ramon</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Evans WH" box="[1308,1440,1797,1824]" pageId="17" pageNumber="16" pagination="10 - 25" refId="ref85025" refString="Evans WH. 1952. A catalogue of the American Hesperiidae indicating the classification and nomenclature adopted in the British Museum (Natural History). Part II. Pyrginae. Section I. British Museum (Natural History). London. v + 178 p., pl. 10 - 25." type="book chapter" year="1952">Evans, 1952</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(type locality 
<collectingCountry box="[343,436,1832,1858]" name="Panama" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">Panama</collectingCountry>
: Bugaba), and not to the species 
<bibRefCitation author="Evans WH" box="[794,939,1831,1858]" pageId="17" pageNumber="16" pagination="10 - 25" refId="ref85025" refString="Evans WH. 1952. A catalogue of the American Hesperiidae indicating the classification and nomenclature adopted in the British Museum (Natural History). Part II. Pyrginae. Section I. British Museum (Natural History). London. v + 178 p., pl. 10 - 25." type="book chapter" year="1952">Evans (1952)</bibRefCitation>
and consequently 
<bibRefCitation author="Austin GT" box="[1145,1299,1831,1858]" pageId="17" pageNumber="16" pagination="1 - 36" refId="ref83857" refString="Austin GT. 2008. Hesperiidae of Rondonia, Brazil: Taxonomic comments on ' night' skippers, with descriptions of new genera and species (Lepidoptera: Eudaminae). Insecta Mundi 29: 1 - 36." type="journal article" year="2008">Austin (2008)</bibRefCitation>
identified as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Mabille and Boullet" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[191,449,1866,1892]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Dyscophellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diaphorus">
<emphasis box="[191,449,1866,1892]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">Dyscophellus diaphorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Mabille and Boullet" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[508,650,1866,1892]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Dyscophellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diaphorus">
<emphasis box="[508,650,1866,1892]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">D. diaphorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<typeStatus box="[656,754,1866,1892]" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">holotype</typeStatus>
will key out to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1952" box="[922,1026,1867,1892]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Dyscophellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ramon">
<emphasis box="[922,1026,1867,1892]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">D. ramon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="Evans WH" box="[1061,1260,1866,1893]" pageId="17" pageNumber="16" pagination="10 - 25" refId="ref85025" refString="Evans WH. 1952. A catalogue of the American Hesperiidae indicating the classification and nomenclature adopted in the British Museum (Natural History). Part II. Pyrginae. Section I. British Museum (Natural History). London. v + 178 p., pl. 10 - 25." type="book chapter" year="1952">Evans (1952: 149)</bibRefCitation>
, because it has a white stripe along the vein 8 (i.e. Sc+R 
<subScript attach="right" box="[614,622,1915,1929]" fontSize="6" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">1</subScript>
) on dorsal hindwing (instead of white basal area of Evans’ “ 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Mabille and Boullet" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[1278,1419,1900,1926]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Dyscophellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diaphorus">
<emphasis box="[1278,1419,1900,1926]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="16">D. diaphorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”) and tawny wing color (instead of more brown). Therefore, in the absence of available synonyms, Austin’s and Evans’ “ 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Mabille and Boullet" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[290,433,1282,1308]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Dyscophellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diaphorus">
<emphasis box="[290,433,1282,1308]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">D. diaphorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” becomes a species without a name, which is given to it here. Description of this species is already provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Evans WH" box="[451,655,1316,1343]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" pagination="10 - 25" refId="ref85025" refString="Evans WH. 1952. A catalogue of the American Hesperiidae indicating the classification and nomenclature adopted in the British Museum (Natural History). Part II. Pyrginae. Section I. British Museum (Natural History). London. v + 178 p., pl. 10 - 25." type="book chapter" year="1952">Evans (1952: 149)</bibRefCitation>
, where it keys out to D.4.8., and complemented by 
<bibRefCitation author="Austin GT" box="[1238,1437,1316,1342]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" pagination="1 - 36" refId="ref83857" refString="Austin GT. 2008. Hesperiidae of Rondonia, Brazil: Taxonomic comments on ' night' skippers, with descriptions of new genera and species (Lepidoptera: Eudaminae). Insecta Mundi 29: 1 - 36." type="journal article" year="2008">Austin (2008: 23)</bibRefCitation>
, who also illustrated its male genitalia in detail (2008: Fig. 100). In brief, the new species is distinguished from its relatives by males with a broad pale area along hindwing costa above, up to about half wing length, preceded by dark basal spot and followed by dark-brown scaling between veins Sc+R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1031,1039,1432,1446]" fontSize="6" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">1</subScript>
and M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1119,1127,1432,1446]" fontSize="6" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">1</subScript>
. This species is most closely related to 
<taxonomicName authority="(E. Bell, 1934)" baseAuthorityName="E. Bell" baseAuthorityYear="1934" box="[304,703,1450,1477]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Dyscophellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="porsena">
<emphasis box="[304,539,1450,1476]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Dyscophellus porsena</emphasis>
(E. Bell, 1934)
</taxonomicName>
(type locality 
<collectingCountry box="[863,918,1451,1477]" name="Peru" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Peru</collectingCountry>
: Iquitos) as revealed by sequencing of its 
<typeStatus pageId="18" pageNumber="17">holotype</typeStatus>
(NVG-15104B04) in AMNH. 
<bibRefCitation author="Austin GT" box="[579,733,1484,1510]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" pagination="1 - 36" refId="ref83857" refString="Austin GT. 2008. Hesperiidae of Rondonia, Brazil: Taxonomic comments on ' night' skippers, with descriptions of new genera and species (Lepidoptera: Eudaminae). Insecta Mundi 29: 1 - 36." type="journal article" year="2008">Austin (2008)</bibRefCitation>
discussed and illustrated 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="E. Bell" baseAuthorityYear="1934" box="[1017,1134,1485,1510]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Dyscophellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="porsena">
<emphasis box="[1017,1134,1485,1510]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">D. porsena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which according to Austin differs from the new species by the pale area at the hindwing costa being confined to near vein Sc+R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1315,1323,1532,1546]" fontSize="6" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">1</subScript>
as a white ray (but it looks more extensive in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="E. Bell" baseAuthorityYear="1934" box="[579,697,1552,1577]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Dyscophellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="porsena">
<emphasis box="[579,697,1552,1577]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">D. porsena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<typeStatus box="[703,803,1551,1577]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">holotype</typeStatus>
, so it remains to be investigated whether this character is variable or Austin misidentified 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="E. Bell" baseAuthorityYear="1934" box="[554,673,1586,1611]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Dyscophellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="porsena">
<emphasis box="[554,673,1586,1611]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">D. porsena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as well) and male genitalia with bulkier uncus, shorter tegumen and narrower valva with somewhat downturned harpe instead of slightly upturned harpe in the new species. The COI DNA barcodes of the new species and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="E. Bell" baseAuthorityYear="1934" box="[623,742,1653,1678]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Dyscophellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="porsena">
<emphasis box="[623,742,1653,1678]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">D. porsena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differ by 5.8% (38 bp), and the new species is identified by the following combination of DNA characters in the barcode: A40C, T59C, A79G, T112C, A238G, T382A, T463C, A494T, and T547C. The COI barcode sequence of the 
<typeStatus box="[796,894,1719,1745]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">holotype</typeStatus>
is:
</paragraph>
